Reference-contexts: Our goal is to extend standard SQL only as far as to make it a reasonable tool to manipulate and retrieve spatial data. The principle demand of `Spatial SQL' is to provide a higher abstraction of spatial data by incorporating concepts closer to humans' perception of space <ref> [Egenhofer, 1994] </ref>. This is accomplished by incorporating the object-oriented concept of user-defined abstract data types (ADT). An ADT is a user-defined atomic type and its associated functions. <p> An extension of SQL must be able to handle queries that fall into three broad categories: 1) Queries which deal exclusively with spatial attributes. 2) Non-spatial queries and 3) queries that combine non-spatial and spatial data. Some of the requirement of spatial query language <ref> [Egenhofer, 1994] </ref> are shown in the following table : Most of these requirements deal with the interaction and display of data. Our focus is more on the functional enhancements of the query language to deal with spatial data.
